package com.example

fun getDefaultMockQuestions(): List<McqField> {
    return listOf(
        McqField(
            subject = "Pathology",
            topic = "Cardiovascular System",
            question = "A 54-year-old male presents to the emergency department with severe, crushing substernal chest pain radiating to his left arm for the past 2 hours. He has a history of uncontrolled hypertension and diabetes mellitus. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in leads V1 to V4. He is immediately taken to the cardiac catheterization lab, and a thrombus in the left anterior descending (LAD) artery is cleared. Six hours later, what is the most likely microscopic pathological change expected in the infarcted myocardial tissue?",
            options = listOf("Infiltration of neutrophilic granulocytes", "Wavy fibers with contraction bands", "Granulation tissue with abundant capillaries", "Dense collagenous scar formation"),
            correct_answer = "B",
            explanation = "<h3><b>Detailed Pathological & Clinical Breakdown:</b></h3><p>This patient presented with an acute Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction (STEMI) due to occlusion of the Left Anterior Descending (LAD) coronary artery. Understanding the temporal sequence of microscopic and macroscopic changes after a myocardial infarction is a <i>highly classic, extremely high-yield topic for NEET PG</i>.</p><h4><b>Temporal Histological Changes in Myocardial Infarction:</b></h4><ul><li><b>0 to 30 mins:</b> No microscopic changes visible on light microscopy. Fully reversible injury.</li><li><b>30 mins to 4 hours:</b> Minimal changes. In some cases, early coagulative necrosis can be seen, but mostly it is unremarkable.</li><li><b>4 to 12 hours:</b> <b>Wavy fibers</b> (elongated, thin myocytes reflecting stretching of dead cells) and early <b>contraction bands</b> (intracellular dense purple bands of hypercontracted sarcomeres caused by calcium influx from reperfusion or leaky membranes) can be seen microscopically.</li><li><b>12 to 24 hours:</b> Progressive coagulative necrosis, pyknosis of nuclei, hypereosinophilic (red) cytoplasm, and early neutrophilic infiltration.</li><li><b>1 to 3 days:</b> Extensive coagulative necrosis with loss of nuclei and striations. Dense infiltration of <b>neutrophils</b> into the interstitial tissue. This is the period of maximum inflammation and risk of fibrinous pericarditis (for transmural infarcts).</li><li><b>3 to 7 days:</b> Macrophages arrive to phagocytose dead myocytes and neutrophil debris. The tissue becomes soft and yellow-brown. <i>Risk of myocardial rupture (free wall, septum, or papillary muscle) reaches its peak during this period (3-7 days)</i> because the collagen matrix has been digested by tissue metalloproteinases but not yet replaced by strong scar tissue.</li><li><b>7 to 10 days:</b> Granulation tissue with abundant newly formed capillaries (neovascularization) and active fibroblasts begins to form at the borders.</li><li><b>10 days to 2 weeks:</b> Well-established granulation tissue with collagen deposition.</li><li><b>2 to 8 weeks:</b> Increased collagen deposition and decreased vascularity.</li><li><b>> 2 months:</b> Completion of a dense, white, hypocellular collagenous <b>scar</b>.</li></ul><h4><b>Differential Diagnosis of Options:</b></h4><ul><li><b>Option A (Infiltration of neutrophils):</b> Occurs predominantly between 1 to 3 days post-MI, not at 6 hours.</li><li><b>Option C (Granulation tissue):</b> Appears at 7 to 10 days.</li><li><b>Option D (Dense collagenous scar):</b> Appears months after the ischemic injury.</li></ul><p><b>NEET PG Key Takeaway:</b> Contraction bands and wavy fibers are the earliest microscopically detectable signs of irreversible myocardial cell death, occurring between 4 to 12 hours post-infarction, heavily highlighted after coronary reperfusion.</p>"
        ),
        McqField(
            subject = "Pharmacology",
            topic = "Autonomic Nervous System",
            question = "A 45-year-old farmer is brought to the emergency department in an obtunded state. His clothes are heavily soiled with a chemical pesticide. On physical examination, he has bilateral pinpoint pupils (miosis), generalized fasciculations, profuse sweating, and bronchorrhea. His blood pressure is 95/60 mmHg and heart rate is 48 beats/min. Which of the following is the mechanism of action of the initial drug of choice for managing this patient's condition?",
            options = listOf("Reactivation of acetylcholinesterase enzyme", "Competitive antagonist of muscarinic acetylcholine receptors", "Direct agonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors", "Irreversible inhibition of butyrylcholinesterase"),
            correct_answer = "B",
            explanation = "<h3><b>Detailed Pharmacological & Clinical Analysis:</b></h3><p>The clinical picture presented—obtunded mental status, miosis, fasciculations, diaphoresis (sweating), cardiology, and severe fluid secretion (bronchorrhea)—is diagnostic of <b>Organophosphate Poisoning</b>. This occurs frequently in agricultural settings due to skin absorption or inhalation of organophosphate pesticides (acetylcholinesterase inhibitors).</p><h4><b>Pathophysiology:</b></h4><p>Organophosphates irreversibly inhibit the enzyme <b>Acetylcholinesterase (AChE)</b> by phosphorylating its active site. This prevents the degradation of acetylcholine, leading to massive accumulation of ACh in both <i>muscarinic</i> and <i>nicotinic</i> synapse receptors:</p><ul><li><b>Muscarinic hyperstimulation (DUMBELS):</b> Diarrhea, Urination, Miosis, Bradycardia/Bronchospasm/Bronchorrhea, Emesis, Lacrimation, Salivation/Sweating.</li><li><b>Nicotinic hyperstimulation:</b> Muscle fasciculations, muscle weakness, and potentially flaccid paralysis (nicotinic block at neuromuscular junctions).</li></ul><h4><b>Management Protocol in Organophosphate Poisoning:</b></h4><p>The immediate life-saving drug of choice is <b>Atropine</b>.</p><ul><li><b>Atropine</b> is a <b>competitive antagonist of muscarinic acetylcholine receptors</b>. It binds to muscarinic receptors and blocks the actions of excess acetylcholine.</li><li><b>Atropine's primary goal:</b> To reverse life-threatening bronchorrhea, bronchospasm, and bradycardia. It has <i>no effect</i> on nicotinic receptors (thus fasciculations and muscle weakness persist).</li><li><b>Atropine Dosing:</b> Double the dose iteratively (1.2mg, 2.4mg, 4.8mg, etc.) every 5-10 minutes until <b>atropinization is achieved</b> (clearing of lung secretions/bronchorrhea, dilated pupils, heart rate > 80 bpm, dry skin).</li></ul><h4><b>Role of Pralidoxime (2-PAM):</b></h4><p><b>Pralidoxime</b> is an AChE regenerator (reactivates the phosphorylated acetylcholinesterase enzyme). It must be given <i>before aging of the enzyme</i> occurs. It reverses both muscarinic and nicotinic hyperstimulation by restoring active enzyme levels. However, it is never used alone; atropine is always given first to control lethal secretions.</p><h4><b>Key Distinctions of Options:</b></h4><ul><li><b>Option A (Reactivation of AChE):</b> Describes Pralidoxime (2-PAM). While crucial, it is a secondary/adjunct agent and not the immediate initial agent used to stabilize severe secretion-related airway block.</li><li><b>Option B (Competitive antagonist of muscarinic receptors):</b> Describes Atropine, the immediate initial drug of choice.</li><li><b>Option C and D:</b> Represent mechanisms that would worsen the cholinergic crisis rather than treat it.</li></ul><p><b>NEET PG High-Yield Summary:</b> In organophosphate poisoning, Atropine blocks muscarinic manifestations and treats the primary cause of death (asphyxiation from bronchorrhea). Pralidoxime (not atropine) reverses neuromuscular nicotinic block by regenerator action on AChE.</p>"
        ),
        McqField(
            subject = "Microbiology",
            topic = "Bacteriology",
            question = "A 32-year-old male who recently returned from a trekking expedition in the rural Western Ghats of India presents with high grade, remittent fever, severe headache, and a dry cough for 5 days. On examination, a painless, 1 cm black, crusted ulcer with an erythematous halo is noted in his right axilla. Laboratory tests reveal thrombocytopenia and elevated transaminases. Weil-Felix reaction shows agglutination with OX-K antigen but not OX-19 or OX-2. What is the most likely causative organism?",
            options = listOf("Rickettsia prowazekii", "Orientia tsutsugamushi", "Rickettsia rickettsii", "Coxiella burnetii"),
            correct_answer = "B",
            explanation = "<h3><b>Detailed Epidemiological & Clinical Case Overview:</b></h3><p>This patient is presenting with classical symptoms of <b>Scrub Typhus</b>, caused by <i>Orientia tsutsugamushi</i>, which is endemic to the tsutsugamushi triangle and highly prevalent in moist, shrubby areas of India (such as the Western Ghats, Himachal Pradesh, etc.).</p><h4><b>Classical Features of Scrub Typhus:</b></h4><ul><li><b>Vector:</b> Transmitted by the bite of larval trombiculid mites (also known as <b>chiggers</b>).</li><li><b>The Eschar:</b> The pathognomonic hallmark is the <b>eschar</b>—a painless, non-itchy black crusted ulcer with a surrounding red halo at the site of the chigger bite. Typically located in intertriginous areas (axilla, groin, neck, abdomen).</li><li><b>Clinical Presentation:</b> Abrupt onset of high fever, severe frontal headache, general lymphadenopathy, dry cough, abdominal pain, and hepatosplenomegaly.</li><li><b>Common Labs:</b> Mild leukopenia or leukocytosis, thrombocytopenia (low platelets), and raised liver enzymes (AST/ALT).</li></ul><h4><b>Understanding Weil-Felix Diagnostic Test:</b></h4><p>The Weil-Felix test is a heterophile antibody test that uses cross-reacting antigens from <i>Proteus vulgaris</i> (OX-19, OX-2) and <i>Proteus mirabilis</i> (OX-K) to deduce rickettsial infections:</p><table><tr><th>Organism</th><th>OX-19</th><th>OX-2</th><th>OX-K</th></tr><tr><td><b>Orientia tsutsugamushi</b></td><td>Negative</td><td>Negative</td><td><b>Positive (OX-K)</b></td></tr><tr><td><b>Rickettsia prowazekii</b></td><td>Positive</td><td>Negative</td><td>Negative</td></tr></table><h4><b>Analysis of Alternative Diagnoses:</b></h4><ul><li><b>Rickettsia prowazekii (Epidemic Typhus):</b> Transmitted by body lice; does not form an eschar; Weil-Felix is positive for OX-19.</li><li><b>Rickettsia rickettsii:</b> Transmitted by ticks; causes a petechial rash starting on ankles and wrists.</li></ul><p><b>NEET PG Gold-Standard Therapy:</b> The drug of choice for Scrub Typhus is <b>Doxycycline</b>. In pregnant patients, <b>Azithromycin</b> is used.</p>"
        ),
        McqField(
            subject = "Obstetrics",
            topic = "Complications of Pregnancy",
            question = "A 28-year-old primigravida at 38 weeks of gestation is brought to the labor room with complaints of a severe, localized, tearing pain in her abdomen for the past hour, accompanied by a small amount of dark vaginal bleeding. On physical examination, her uterus is stony hard, exquisitely tender, and does not relax between contraction intervals. Fetal heart rate monitoring shows severe bradycardia (80 bpm) with late decelerations. What is the most definitive immediate step in management?",
            options = listOf("Amniotomy and starting Oxytocin infusion", "Emergency Caesarean Section", "Tocolytic therapy with Nifedipine", "Administration of intramuscular Betamethasone"),
            correct_answer = "B",
            explanation = "<h3><b>Detailed Clinical & Obstetric Analysis:</b></h3><p>This clinical presentation is classic for a major <b>Abruptio Placentae</b> (premature separation of a normally implanted placenta before delivery of the fetus).</p><h4><b>Classic Diagnostic Triad of Abruptions:</b></h4><ol><li><b>Abdominal Pain:</b> Severe, sudden-onset, localized tearing abdominal pain that is persistent (unlike uterine contraction cycles which wax and wane).</li><li><b>Uterine Rigidity (Stony Hard Uterus):</b> The uterus is hypertonic, tender, and fails to relax. This is due to high intra-amniotic pressure and hemorrhage dissecting into the myometrium (called a <b>Couvelaire Uterus</b>).</li><li><b>Dark Vaginal Bleeding:</b> May or may not match the severity of internal blood loss (revealed vs. concealed hemorrhage).</li></ol><h4><b>Fetal Compromise Signs:</b></h4><p>The late decelerations and persistent bradycardia indicate severe fetal hypoxia due to loss of functional placental surface area. The fetus is actively undergoing distress.</p><h4><b>Management Plan:</b></h4><p>In cases of placental abruption with <b>fetal distress</b> (bradycardia, late decelerations) at term (38 weeks), the definitive treatment is <b>immediate Emergency Caesarean Section</b> to save the baby and control maternal hemorrhage.</p><h4><b>Critical Evaluation of Other Options:</b></h4><ul><li><b>Option A (Amniotomy & Oxytocin):</b> Indicated in abruption only if the fetus is already dead (intrauterine fetal demise) or if the cervix is fully dilated and safe vaginal delivery is imminent within minutes. However, here we have an active live distressed fetus requiring immediate rescue.</li><li><b>Option C (Tocolytic therapy):</b> Absolutely contraindicated in placental abruption. Relaxing the uterus would promote maternal bleeding and further hypoperfusion of the placenta.</li><li><b>Option D (Betamethasone):</b> Given to promote fetal lung maturity. It is indicated only in pregnancies < 34 weeks. This patient is at term (38 weeks).</li></ul><p><b>NEET PG High-Yield Summary:</b> Placental abruption presents as painful dark bleeding with a rigid, tender uterus. If fetal distress is present at term, manage immediately with emergency Caesarean. If the fetus is dead, prioritize vaginal delivery with induction/amniotomy unless maternal complications query a cesarean.</p>"
        )
    )
}
